feat: Add flag for specifying the the VID model line
body:
Support VID Model Line rollout using Reporting Server flags. Two flags are added:

–default-vid-model-line=<String>
Specifies the VID model line value to be used for the “model_line” field in MeasurementSpec This in turn determines what VID model line that EDPs will use to fulfill Requisitions. If empty EDPs must agree offline what the default is. Once enabled we encourage that this case become an error.

–measurement-consumer-vid-model-line=Map<String, String>
A map of MC names to model lines. When a Metric is created, if the Metric is for an MC present in this map, then the model line provided as the value will be used for the  “model_line” field in MeasurementSpec.

ci: Read Spanner processing units from GitHub environment
body:
Different Halo test environments have different Spanner resource needs. For example, the `head` environment tends to have much lower traffic compared to the `qa` environment. Spanner autoscaling only supports whole nodes (multiples of 1000 processing units), whereas some test environments are often idle and do not need a whole node. Spanner nodes are relatively expensive (currently $657/month for the us-central1 region).

This also removes the specification of 100 processing nodes for the example Terraform configuration, as that is far below Spanner recommendations.

body: The current threshold (3.291 x sigma) guarantees that each noisy measurement is 99.9% within the confidence interval. However, the integration tests consist of at least 30 independent noisy values. This pushes the failure rate to (1-0.999^30 ~ 0.03), which is a bit high and causes the presubmit test to be flaky. Increasing this threshold to 5 x sigma will bring the failure rate down to below 0.0001.

title: fix: Throw StorageException as TransientError from the mill
body:
According to the practice of stress testing, given that[ common-jvm](https://github.com/world-federation-of-advertisers/common-jvm/blob/main/src/main/kotlin/org/wfanet/measurement/gcloud/gcs/GcsStorageClient.kt#L68-L70) already have retry mechanism for retryable exceptions, gcs writing still pops up unretryable exceptions which actually looks retryable. (Unexpected Error code 504 trying to get security access token from Compute Engine metadata for the default service account: Gateway Timeout)
This PR makes the error from storage transient so that the mill will retry it after the period of time.

title: Prepare example Kingdom-less exchange daemon for GKE.
body:
Summary:
* Creates `.cue` files for deploying Kingdom-less daemon to GKE.
* Adds Kingdom-less daemon flags.
    * Uses `@ArgGroup` to ensure mutual exclusitivity between Kingdom-based flags and Kingdom-less flags.
    * Updates the example daemon main class to build the correct type of `ApiClient` and `CertificateManager` based on which group of flags was set.
* Several other tweaks to make the deployment work:
    * Factory function for building a shared storage client needed to be `suspend`ing.
    * Explicitly call `withDefaultCredentails()` when building `GcpKmsClient`. This used to happen by default, but seems to have been (inadvertently?) removed in a previous PR.
    * In `KingdomlessApiClient.kt`:
        * Make sure that `ExchangeWorkflowDependencyGraph` is built in step order. The dependency graph will throw if e.g. you try to mark a step as completed before its prerequisite steps.
        * Add retries when loading checkpoints from shared storage, as a temporary measure to mitigate race conditions. A longer term solution will be to add a direct upload option to `StorageClient`, but need to investigate this further.

body:
Updates most of the panel match code to remove dependencies on classes in the `org.wfanet.measurement.api.v2alpha` package.

Most of the interesting changes are in the `src/main/kotlin/org/wfanet/panelmatch/client/launcher` directory, where some of the core interfaces for claiming and launching exchange tasks have been changed slightly.

A small number of dependencies on the v2alpha API still remain:

* `ProtoConversions.kt` - This class is specifically meant for converting the v2alpha messages into the panel match internal ones.
* `ExchangeWorkflowDaemonFromFlags.kt` and related integration test classes - These will continue to depend on v2alpha -- or the whatever the current API version is -- as long as there is an option for running Kingdom-based exchanges.
* `GrpcApiClient.kt` and `V2AlphaCertificateManager.kt` - Same as the previous bullet. These will continue to be used by any daemon that runs a Kingdom-based exchange.
* A few standalone tools continue to support the v2alpha message definitions alongside the new internal ones.

title: Add etag support to system ComputationParticipant.
Propose updates to decouple panel match client from v2alpha API
body:
This PR proposes a set of updates to decouple the panel match client libraries from the v2alpha API.

This is **NOT** intended to be merged as-is, but rather to prove the feasibility of decoupling and to gather some initial feedback on the overall approach. If there are no major concerns, I will split this into several smaller PRs and send those for separate review.

**This PR touches a lot of files. The interesting bits are mostly in `src/main/kotlin/org/wfanet/panelmatch/client/launcher` if you just need to get the gist.**

---

Summary of changes:
* Introduces panel match internal versions of `ExchangeWorkflow` and `ExchangeStepAttempt` protobuf messages.
    * Exchange task logic now uses the internal `ExchangeWorkflow` exclusively.
    * Relevant tools have been updated to accept a `--exchange-workflow-format` flag to be compatible with both the v2alpha messages and the new internal ones. Supported formats are:
        * `V2ALPHA` - For exchanges that continue to use the Kingdom-based protocol with v2alpha messages.
        * `KINGDOMLESS` - For exchanges that have adopted the upcoming Kingdom-less protocol with panel match internal messages.
* Code related to claiming / validating / launching exchange tasks updated as follows:
    * `ApiClient.ClaimedExchangeStep` - Updated to remove references to v2alpha concepts. Notable changes:
        * The `attemptKey` for a step is now a panel match internal `ExchangeStepAttemptKey` with mostly the same info as before but no references to a "resource name".
        * Rather than creating a panel match internal `ExchangeStep` message, instead ported the necessary fields directly into `ClaimedExchangeStep`. These are: `exchangeDate`, `stepIndex`, and `workflow`.
        * **New field:** `workflowFingerprint`. When a claimed exchange step is being validated, the existing logic compares the serialized workflow returned by the Kingdom against the serialized workflow in private storage. I'm proposing that we now compare _fingerprints_ of the serialized workflows. These may be fingerprints of v2alpha workflows or the new panel match internal workflow - depending on the concrete implementation of `ApiClient`.
    * With the removal of `ExchangeStep`, the exchange task validator now accepts a `ApiClient.ClaimedExchangeStep`.

body:
Update the Reporting CLI tool to create a UI readable report. It is moderately hardcoded to limit the amount of configuration required by the user. There are a number of steps to complete this process:
1. Create 3 primitive Reporting Sets (with a number of event groups).
2. Create 1 union Reporting Set - the union of all 3 primitives.
3. Create 3 unique Reporting Sets (difference between the union and the union of the other two. eg. unique A = ABC - BC)
4. Create 1 metric calculation spec for the primitives.
5. Create 1 metric calculation spec for the composites.
6. Create a report mapping the reporting sets and metric calculation specs and include the other report parameters (like date range and frequency).

All the reporting sets and the report will be tagged appropriately so the Reporting BFF can process the report correctly.

The addBinding method executes one update per row. When the number of rows is large, the performance suffers. For 800 measurements, update takes 1.4 seconds locally. With the change in this PR,  update takes 0.8 seconds.

The refactoring is done this way because R2DBC doesn't automically transform the update into a single batch update. See https://github.com/pgjdbc/r2dbc-postgresql/issues/527.

The addBinding method executes one insert per row. When the number of rows is large, the performance suffers. For 800 metrics with one measurement each and the same reporting set for each metric, insertion takes 4.2 seconds locally. With the change in this PR, insertion takes 1.4 seconds.

The refactoring is done this way because R2DBC doesn't automically transform the inserts into a single batch insert. See [https://github.com/pgjdbc/r2dbc-postgresql/issues/527](https://github.com/pgjdbc/r2dbc-postgresql/issues/527).

Output uniformly random guess at frequency distribution when reach is too small
body: The variance calculation of frequency distribution will output `NaN` when reach is zero. Moreover, the estimated variance is not accurate when reach is impractically small. The solution is to check whether the reach is too small using its confidence interval. If the confidence interval of the reach contains values <= 0, we claim the reach is too small for an accurate variance estimate of frequency distribution, and output the variance of uniformly random draw from [0, 1].

After this update, for the first non-aggregator, the normal stage transition is:
 INITIALIZED -> WAIT_TO_START -> SETUP_PHASE ->
WAIT_ON_SHUFFLE_INPUT_PHASE_TWO -> SHUFFLE_PHASE
-> COMPLETE

For the second non-aggregator, the normal stage transition is:
INITIALIZED -> WAIT_ON_SHUFFLE_INPUT_PHASE_ONE -> SETUP_PHASE
-> SHUFFLE_PHASE -> COMPLETE

For the aggregator, the normal stage transition is:
WAIT_ON_AGGREGATION_INPUT -> AGGREGATION_PHASE -> COMPLETE

title: Updating Charts and fixing some Chart Bugs
body:
Notes:
* Chart features:
  * Adding a new chart type (multi-bar not percentage).
  * Updating existing draw bar function (was removed from use so last PR didn't break anything).
  * Adding a legend.
  * Updating chart titles.
* Chart bugs:
  * Setting a max height on the charts so they can always be viewable in a screen.

Use Bazel remote cache in GCS instead of GitHub Actions cache.
body:
This avoids GitHub Actions cache limits, which at present only allow a single build to be cached. As a result, the build cache is currently only written after merging into `main`, evicting the previous cache. Using Bazel's remote caching with a GCS bucket in halo-cmm-dev allows the cache to be written to by any branch, as the cache works at the action level. This instead only relies on the GitHub Actions cache to hold the Bazel repository cache.

This also enables pinning for Maven artifacts, as that allows Maven artifacts to use Bazel's repository cache.

See https://bazel.build/remote/caching and https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_jvm_external/blob/6.0/README.md#pinning-artifacts-and-integration-with-bazels-downloader

title: Support sampling for synthetic event group spec
body:
**Consider the following problem** for generating synthetic data for 3 Edps that represents a realistic intersection
Using the current [VidRange field](https://github.com/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/blob/119d42385f5f56da7d28693d0987a9aa0bdd53aa/src/main/proto/wfa/measurement/api/v2alpha/event_group_metadata/testing/simulator_synthetic_data_spec.proto#L108)
Edp1 range -> (0,100)
Edp2 range -> (50,150) [At this point we have 50 intersection for Edp1 and 2]
Edp3 range -> ?? [How should we decide on this]

**Here are 2 possible solutions** :  
1. Sample Vids from those ranges given a sample size for each vidRange.
2. Another way is to sample n ranges from the larger range while creating the [SyntheticEventGroupSpec](https://github.com/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/blob/119d42385f5f56da7d28693d0987a9aa0bdd53aa/src/main/proto/wfa/measurement/api/v2alpha/event_group_metadata/testing/simulator_synthetic_data_spec.proto#L97) and approximate. 

This PR is the implementation of the first option

title: Refactor Report Time
Task expiration spanner fix
body:
Specifically: if attempt has caused a temporary failure, we do not update the status of the task to READY_TO_RETRY if the attempt being marked as failed is not the latest attempt.

Justification: We have noticed that there are cases where multiple
IN_PROGRESS attempts exist for a single task. 
  - Whether those are active or not is unclear, but the result of this was if any fail or time out the task is set to READY_TO_RETRY while other attempts are currently IN_PROGRESS (which is not desirable). 
  - If there is somehow a newer attempt than the one being finished, we trust _that_ attempt will update the task state when it completes or times out and therefore the task is not, in fact, ready to retry.

WAIT_ON_INPUT stage is changed into WAIT_ON_SHUFFLE_INPUT or WAIT_ON_AGGREGATION_INPUT

INITIALIZED -> SETUP_PHASE -> **(WAIT_ON_SHUFFLE_INPUT)** -> SHUFFLE_PHASE-> COMPLETE

For the aggregator, the normal stage transition is:
**WAIT_ON_AGGREGATION_INPUT** -> AGGREGATION_PHASE -> COMPLETE

title: Add a metric reuse mechanism based on timed ReportingMetricEntries
body:
Given the fact that `MetricCalculationSpec` is now an individual resource and can be reused, we can utilize this to identify a set of metrics across reports. Note that the granularity is "a set of metrics" that is associated with `MetricCalculationSpec`.

When a `MetricCalculationSpec` is reused in a different report, by identifying the pair of `MetricCalculationSpec` and the `ReportingSet` and the `TimeInterval`s from the report, we are able to identify the existing set of metrics created from the previous reports. This could be done during the internal report creation by the following:
1. Left join the table `Metrics` and `MetricCalculationSpecReportingMetrics` by `MeasurementConsumerId` and `MetricId`.
2. Find the set of metrics given `MeasurementConsumerId`, `ReportingSetId`, `MetricCalculationSpecId`, a set of `TimeIntervalStart` and `TimeIntervalEndExclusive`.
3. Repeat the process for all `ReportingMetricEntries`, i.e. pairs of `MetricCalculationSpecs` and `ReportingSets`.

At the step (2) above, the reason why we could get a set of metrics is because a `MetricCalculationSpec` could correspond to multiple metrics due to the fan-out of metric types, groupings, and time intervals.

title: Create Dynamic Clipping library for impression measurement
body:
### Background
* For impression/duration measurements, we have to set an impression/duration cap to guarantee differential privacy
* Currently, the measurement consumers(MC) select the cap, but it's challenging for MCs since the optimal cap should be chosen based on the frequency/duration distribution
* The Dynamic Clipping library allows the EDP to automatically optimize the cap for each campaign and to achieve higher accuracy than using a fixed cap, based on the frequency distribution of the events

### Need to Know
The Dynamic Clipping library is provided as a reference implementation for EDP to potentially improve impression/duration measurement accuracy. It is an optional EDP feature, and will require additional local market approval for deployment in production.

### Reference
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1vboqbbHOqblYhooYCwAJ2fyqBCZOILFKmxtCm_O-kaY/edit

Rally task link: https://rally1.rallydev.com/#/?detail=/task/729250522061&fdp=true

body:
## TL;DR
Using variances instead of fixed tolerance values for checking measurement values. 

## What changed
### FrequencyDistributionSubject.kt
- Add a `isWithin` function to compare actual and expected using a tolerance map.

### MeasurementConsumerSimulator.kt
- Add a function to compute reach variances.
- Add a function to compute the margin of error of a 99.9% Confidence Interval (CI).
- Add a function to compute tolerances for relative frequency results.
- Check if reach results and frequency results are within 99.9% CI. 

## Why make this change
Previous checks on measurement results were using fixed tolerance values which is hardcoded and not meaningful. Using CIs provides a statistical way to make sure that the noised results fall into a reasonable range.

title: Improve Performance of Measurement Creation in Create Report
body: I tested a Report that created 300 measurements using a PeriodicTimeInterval with 300 increments. On a GKE cluster (e2-standard-2), it originally took ~60 seconds. With this PR, it takes ~30 seconds. Adding BatchCreateMeasurements to the internal Reporting server led to the bulk of the improvement. Caching the GetDataProvider and GetCertificate calls didn't lead to a large improvement. The measurement creation flow (Create Kingdom Measurements -> Create Reporting Measurements) occupies the bulk of the time. The only thing I could think of to further improve the performance is to add BatchCreateMeasurements to the Kingdom Public API.

title: Fix bug on rollv2 that outputs zero reach if the execution phase crashes right after writing to the output blob.
body:
In the execution phase of reach only protocols, the aggregator first initializes the reach to 0. It then runs an existingOutputOr block to compute the next token. If the output blob is empty, it updates the reach and writes stuff to the output blob. Otherwise, it skips the block, reuses the cache results and sends the reach to the kingdom.

There is a problem when the output blob exists, but the aggregator crashes before sending the reach to the kingdom. As the existingOutputOr block is skipped, the reach will not be updated and will stay at the initialized value (i.e. 0). As a result, the kingdom will receive 0.

title: Refactoring the LiquidLegionsV2Mill and ReachOnlyLiquidLegionsV2Mill
body:
Currently, the two classes LiquidLegionsV2Mill and ReachOnlyLiquidLegionsV2Mill share some common code (e.g. the functions verifyEdpParticipation, verifyDuchySignature, failComputationAtConfirmationPhase, sendResultToKingdom, nextDuchyStub, aggregatorDuchyStub, ComputationToken.participantCount). A base class, called LiquidLegionsV2MillBase, will be created to own these common pieces.

On top of the above functions, the two mills behave similarly in the initialization and confirmation phase. On the surface, it makes sense to also unify these behaviors inside the LiquidLegionsV2MillBase class. However, the effort to achieve this goal is high. As the protobufs, crypto code, and kotlin code of the two protocols are almost separated, having an abstract function for initialization/confirmation phase would require unifying the protobufs, crypto code, and kotlin code.

The tests for the two protocols remain unchanged to reflect the existing implementation.

Add metric variances to metric results in reporting v2
body:
Compute metric variances in a report using the `Variances` library. Any insufficiency of inputs to the variance calculation will not set `univariate_statistics`.

* Reach: compute variances from weighted reach measurements.
* Frequency histogram: compute variances from weighted reach and frequency measurements.
* Impression count: compute variances only when the operation is union-only. The variance of an impression metric is the sum of the weighted impression results.
* Watch duration: compute variances only when the operation is union-only. The variance of a duration metric is the sum of the weighted duration results.

body:
## TL;DR
This pull request introduces a validation check for frequency histogram metrics to ensure they are only computed on union-only set expressions. It also updates the unit test name of when a reporting set is not accessible to the caller and adds a test case for the new validation check.

## What changed
1. In `MetricsService.kt`, a validation check was added to ensure that frequency histogram metrics are only computed on union-only set expressions. If this condition is not met, an `INVALID_ARGUMENT` error is thrown.
2. The name of the test case `createMetric throws INVALID_ARGUMENT when reporting set is not accessible to caller` was updated to `createMetric throws PERMISSION_DENIED when reporting set is not accessible to caller`.
3. A new test case `createMetric throws INVALID_ARGUMENT when Frequency Histogram metric is computed on non-union-only set expression` was added in `MetricsServiceTest.kt`.
4. Comments were added in `metric.proto` to provide more context about the conditions under which univariate statistics are computed.
 
## Why make this change
This change ensures that frequency histogram metrics are computed correctly and provides more informative error messages to the user. It also improves the clarity of the code by adding explanatory comments.

body:
Roll out Gaussian noise and ACDP composition by changing the default values of `noise_mechanism` to `DISCRETE_GAUSSIAN` in testing configs for the LLV2 protocols, and `compositionMechanism` to `ACDP` in EDP simulator. By changing `noise_mechanism` to `DISCRETE_GAUSSIAN`, Duchy will add discrete Gaussian noise distributedly to MPC measurements. And by changing compositionMechanism to ACDP, PBM in EDP simulator will use ACDP composition for privacy accounting, and EDP simulator will add continuous Gaussian noise to direct measurements.

The changes will be effective in the Halo QA environment as well as in InProcessLifeOfAMeasurementIntegrationTest and EmptyClusterCorrectnessTest.

title: Store measurement computation details in reporting for error bars
body:
In addition to storing results in the internal measurements, we also store the computation details about the measurement creation. The structure of the internal measurement result is now same as the one in Kingdom -- measurement results are in a list to represent results from different data providers; noise mechanisms and computation methodologies are added to `Result`. Note that unlike the Kingdom `Result` which stores only direct noise mechanisms and direct methodologies, here we store both direct and MPC noise mechanisms and methodologies.

The additional computation details can be used to compute measurement variances and potentially used to identify measurements. No DB change is needed as the changes happened in `Details`.

Adding the List Reports view to the Reporting UI.
To support the MVVM pattern we chose, these pieces were added:
- view: renders the content with high level UI logic (like showing loading and error components).
- view model: the glue to hook up the view with the model.
- repository: a UI model (not the API model) that includes knowledge of API calls to make and translating the API models into UI models.
- component: any view specific components to help increase readability.

Other supporting feature:
- routing: there's only one view right now, but routing is easy to add and we'll need it anyways.

EDP simulator supports ACDP composition
body:
Update EDP simulator to support ACDP composition. Currently keep using the old DP_ADVANCED composition with MPC Geometric(Laplace) noise and direct Laplace noise for backward compatibility. Once MPC DP noise is switched to Discrete Gaussian noise in Kingdom, and direct DP noise is switched to Gaussian in EDP simulator, change compositionMechasnim to ACDP and start using ACDP composition in PBM. 

ACDP composition can only be used with MPC discrete Gaussian or direct Gaussian noise. Otherwise, the requisition will be refused. The old DP_ADVANCED PBM ledger and composition methods, old PrivacyBucketCharges BackingStore table should be deprecated/deleted after migration to ACDP is completed/stabilized.

Major changes in this PR:
* Create a new CompositionMechasnim flag(DP_ADVANCED, ACDP) in EdpSimulatorFlags
* EDP simulator supports charging privacy budget in ACDP composition
* Charge privacy budget for direct measurements
* Add EDP simulator unit tests for the new ACDP methods

body:
In this PR, the implementation of the [API changes in CMM-API](https://github.com/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement-api/pull/163) is done. The main changes are 
1. new direct protocol config,
2. additional info in measurement results,
3. new enum constants in `ProtocolConfig.NoiseMechanism`,
4. EDP simulator choose the noise mechanism based on the overlap of its preferences and the noise mechanism options in the direct protocol config.

Any future measurement creations will contain certain direct protocol configs based on the measurement types. For the backward compatibility for existing measurements and requisitions, the empty internal direct protocol configs will be converted with the options that would have been valid at the time the Measurement was created.

EDPs are restricted to use continuous noise mechanisms by setting the validation in `V2alphaPublicApiServer`. Discrete Gaussian will be supported in the future.

title: Implementation of the initialization, setup, and execution phase of the reach-only protocol.
body:
Implement the phases of the new sparse reach only protocol:

1. Initialization phase: Duchies sample local El Gamal keypair.
2. Setup phase:
a) Non-aggregators add noise registers to the crv and shuffle the modified crv. They encrypt their excessive noise using the composite El Gamal public key. They send the crv and the excessive noise ciphertext to the aggregator.
b) Aggregator: Waits for the crv and the excessive noise ciphertexts from non-aggregators. It adds noise to the crv, shuffles it, and encrypts its excessive noise with the composite El Gamal key. It then combines the excessive noise ciphertexts by adding them together. It sends the modified crv and the excessive noise ciphertext to the next worker.
3. Execution phase: Duchies collaborate to decrypt, randomize the register indices, and decrypt the excessive noise ciphertext. The aggregator can count the number of distinct registers, obtain the total amount of excessive noise, then estimate the reach based on the available information.

title: Add MultithreadingHelper to refactor multithreaded LLV2
body:
## Background
To multithread the execution of LLV2. Currently all for-loops are single-threaded but iterations are actually independent. They can be refactored into a multi-threading pattern.
Most operations rely on [ProtocolCryptor](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/-/blob/src/main/cc/wfa/measurement/common/crypto/protocol_cryptor.cc). Unfortunately, the class ProtocolCryptor is not thread-safe. Thus, multiple identical ProtocolCryptors must be created and each thread should have a dedicated ProtocolCryptor. 
Current iterations append results directly to the output variable. This is not a good pattern for multiple threading if the order matters because the execution order of iterations is not deterministic.

## Design 
The general idea is to have a helper class assigning tasks to multiple threads and collect output after execution.
### Parameters
The helper has three primary parameters: data, # iterations, and a lambda expression.
The lambda expression reuses current code as the task to run. Given data and # iterations, the helper execute the lambda expression with index from 0 to (# iterations -1). Thus, the helper can split tasks even if the input is in batch as a variable `data`.
Capture list of the lambda expression has all the variables to execute iterations. No major change required from current for-loop block. 
### Results
Lambda expression is responsible for handling results from iterations and making sure it is thread-safe.
### Cryptors
The ProtocolCryptor is not thread-safe. Each thread should have its own ProtocolCryptor to execute lambda expressions.
The helper can be reused multiple times with different types of input and output. ProtocolCryptor only needs to be initialized once. For example SetupPhase, it has multiple for-loops to add various types of noise. Only one helper need to create and reuse.
Some procedure does not require ProtocolCryptor thus can skip `setupCryptors`.

## Class Interface
See the header file.

## Usage
See the unit test.

Derive metric states
body:
Motivation:

* In the current design, the metric state is updated using a on-demand strategy -- only updated when the public `get` or `list` is called. This causes the internal metric state is not consistent with what the states of the associated measurements indicate. For example, a metric might have all measurements with SUCCEEDED states, but itself is PENDING. 



Design change:

* The metric state is essentially a derivative from the states of the associated measurements. Therefore, we could instead determine the metric state in the public server call and remove the state column in the internal metrics DB.

* Similarly, the metric result can be calculated easily on the public side, so we don't need to store metric result in the database.

title: Add created and updated before fields to stream measurements filter
Add flag to config mill retry backoff delay base.
body:
Two Questions to solve:
1. For duchy's api `enqueue()`, do we need extra check to see if the token's lock owner is the same as current token?
No. The computationService checks whether the token is the latest version which guarantees that the lockowner in the request must be the same as the current lockowner. 
Currently this api is only used by mills to request retries for failed computations.

2. Do we need mill's retry backoff mechanism given the FIFO behavior for computations.
Yes. It is good-to-have feature. When we set backoff base to 0, it means mills should immediately retry failed computations (because they are the oldest, of course). On the other side, we might want the mills to calm down and work on other computations. Thus this mechanism add a cooldown time for retriable computations.

title: Update duchy to handle reach-only requests
body: If reach_and_frequency.maximum_frequency_per_user is set to 1 in the MeasurementSpec for a ReachAndFrequency request, then an alternative path is followed for handling the request. This alternative path differs from the standard path in the following ways: 1. The Duchy sets the key for each register to "destroyed" and sets the count to a random value. 2. Frequency-related noise registers are not added to the sketch. 3. After the reach value has been computed, the protocol terminates early and returns just this value. - - - This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/676)

title: Remove infinite loop that occurs when duchies generate exceptions
body: There are numerous reasons why exceptions can occur during the processing of a measurement request. One example is when an invalid value of delta is given, but many others can be found by grepping for 'error' in the code. When an exception is generated, the Herald enters an infinite loop of continuously retrying the request that generated the exception. This pull request eliminates this infinite loop. Unfortunately, this is only part of work that has to be done to correct the way in which exceptions are handled. It appears that currently, the herald has no way of propagating exceptions back to the kingdom. Consequently, a failed computation will permanently appear to be in progress and will never progress to the COMPLETED or FAILED state, and the measurement consumer will never learn why their computation failed. This will take more significant rework, which is deferred to a future PR. --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/608)

title: Reject zero values of delta
body: The differential privacy protocols currently in use for Liquid Legions v2 require that delta > 0. If a 0 value of delta was supplied, the C++ code for sketch creation and noising would generate an exception, causing the duchy to crash. This patch causes the herald to check for a non-zero value of delta before further processing is allowed. If a zero value is found, then the Herald generates an exception. --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/607)

title: Allow ResourceSetup to retry its first request to the Kingdom
body: The resource-setup-job is typically executed immediately after the deployment of gcp-kingdom-data-server, and resource-setup-job depends on gcp-kingdom-data-server because it makes requests to it in order to obtain various configuration values. However, gcp-kingdom-data-server often takes significantly longer to initialize than resource-setup-job. This can cause the resource-setup-job to timeout and fail, which then breaks the deployment. This patch allows the resource-setup-job to perform multiple retries of its first request to gcp-kingdom-data-server, so this potential breakage is avoided. --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/601)

title: Catch KingdomInternalException and throw Grpc errors
body: Issue: https://github.com/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/issues/247 When a specific resource is not found, use `FAILED_PRECONDITION`, `INVALID_ARGUMENT` or `NOT_FOUND`? As `INVALID_ARGUMENT` is more about the format of arguments, avoid to use it in our cases. When the major entity is not found, use `NOT_FOUND`. For example, if `getMeasurement` or `updateMeasurement` fail to find the `Measurement`, we call it `NOT_FOUND`. Other than the major entity, use `FAILED_PRECONDITION`. For example, for `getMeasurement` or `updateMeasurement`, if `Account`/`MeasurementConsumer`/`Certificate` not found, call it `FAILED_PRECONDITION`. This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/559)

body: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1BHhO6gRgMPtlLHQSzc1rhS8hVWfn0BJF_gXU3T-cXio/edit# 1. KingdomInternalException is now a sealed class. Each error code has 1 or more derivative class to create the instance of internal exception with required contextual information. For example, `MEASUREMENT_CONSUMER_NOT_FOUND` has one class `MeasurementConsumerNotFound` requiring `externalMeasurementConsumerId` as context info `MEASUREMENT_NOT_FOUND` has two classes: `MeasurementNotFoundByComputation` requires `externalComputationId`; `MeasurementNotFoundByMeasurementConsumer` requires `externalMeasurementConsumerId` and `externalMeasurementId`. `CERITIFICATE_NOT_FOUND` is complicated. It has `DataProviderCertificateNotFoundByExternal`, `DataProviderCertificateNotFoundByInternal`, `MeasurementConsumerCertificateNotFoundByExternal`, `MeasurementConsumerCertificateNotFoundByInternal` and `DuchyCertificateNotFound`. (Please share your thought if any other idea) 2. Applied the new mechanism to exception throwers. In .../spanner/writers/ConfirmComputationParticipant.kt, one of the errors should be `MeasurementStateIllegal` in stead of `ComputationParticipantStateIllegal`. title: Create postgres backing store for the privacy budget management ledger
body: Adds a new class `PostgresBackingStore`, which implements a `PrivacyBudgetLedgerBackingStore` that uses a single JDBC Connection, and implements transactions natively through SQL. In addition: * Makes the BackingStore and TransactionContext implement Closeable (to make sure transactions are either commited or rolledback and connections are closed) * Transactions can't be nested (given the limitation of one SQL transaction per JDBC connection) - ideally each thread should use it's own `PostgresBackingStore` instance, so the test simulates this * Adds `PostgresBackingStoreTest`, based on the changes listed above. It uses `EmbeddedPostgres` to run the tests. --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/533)

title: Ensure an exchange step is not its own prerequisite.
body: In general, exchange steps should not have the same blob key in both their input map and output map, as this causes the step to be its own prerequisite and thus can never enter a READY state. The only exception is CopyFromPreviousExchangeStep which must have the same input and output blob key in order to work correctly. For this type of step, explicitly remove its index from the prerequisite indices so that it can be properly scheduled. --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/489)

title: Fix the GKE correctnessTest deployment.
body: The test was broken since we have made plenty changes to the system. For example, principal authority and mark variables related changes. The PR also 1. uploaded a synthetic-labelled-events.csv for completing correctnessTest on GKE 2. switched the order of EDP and MC creation in the resourceSetupJob to make sure we call the kingdom public API first. Otherwise, the job may call the internal kingdom API successfully and fail later when calling the public API. If this happens, the retry would fail constantly since the EDPs are already created. 3. title: Run docker containers as nonroot
body: `distroless` containers run as root but [have a non-root user build in by default](https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_docker/issues/1678). We can try to pull in `nonroot` tagged images for our docker images or set the user to `nonroot`. I went with the later option but ran into issues. Paging the bazel experts @wangyaopw @efoxepstein @SanjayVas - I tried adding a new `container_image` rule that we can use as the base but when building bazel complains with ``` File "/local/home/ohardt/cdd2/Users/ohardt/workplace/WFA/cross-media-measurement/src/main/docker/java_image_base_nonroot.bzl", line 3, column 16, in container_image( File "/local/home/ohardt/.cache/bazel/_bazel_ohardt/a80ab98a267f72a094ee67d1306318a3/external/io_bazel_rules_docker/container/image.bzl", line 875, column 21, in container_image container_image_(**kwargs) Error in container_image_: Cannot instantiate a rule when loading a .bzl file. Rules may be instantiated only in a BUILD thread. ``` Any suggestions on where can/should I put the base container image rule so it's not failing? --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/296)

title: Don't use runIfTokenFromlastUpdate for writeRequisitionBlobPath().
body: It is causing an issue when multiple EDPs are fulfilling their requisitions at the same time. There is no need to require the caller of writeRequisitionBlobPath() to own the most recent token. writeRequisitionBlobPath() is called by the requsitionFulfillmentService, which doesn't claim the lock of a computation before updating it. https://rally1.rallydev.com/#/604612930531d/userstories?detail=%2Ftask%2F609964597029&view=2c2927c0-626b-4740-8620-af2a93b7d623 --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/world-federation-of-advertisers/cross-media-measurement/289)

title: Split apart KingdomRelationalDatabase.
body:
This moves functionality into super-interfaces of
KingdomRelationalDatabase. This also splits out test-only logic into a
test-only database helper class.

The next steps are:

1. Split apart implementations of KingdomRelationalDatabase into
implementations of the super-interface.

2. Transition clients of KingdomRelationalDatabase to clients of the
super-interfaces.

3. Delete KingdomRelationalDatabase.

These changes are important because, as part of #3, a fair amount of
new database functionality is needed. However, most clients only need a
tiny subset of the exposed interface. By splitting it up, we are able to
logically isolate functionality and narrow the public interfaces seen by
most clients.

and is not suitable for using in production. Deleting it such that we
don't need to maintain it anymore.
* Proto fields and enum indexes update is safe since no code is in
production.
